Research Officer - Computer Science (Fixed Term 3 Yrs)

<https://www.bath.ac.uk/jobs/Vacancy.aspx?ref=3DVH1457>

Salary:   Starting from =A330,424, rising to =A336,298
Closing Date:   Wednesday 23 January 2013
Interview Date:   To be confirmed
Reference:  VH1457

The post is associated with the three-year EPSRC=20
project "Efficient and Natural Proof Systems".=20
The project is about developing an ambitious,=20
modern semantic-motivated proof theory for=20
representing natural proofs of minimal complexity.

We are looking for a researcher who can work with=20
categorical models of proofs and who has an=20
interest in geometric proof representations such=20
as proof nets and atomic flows. The main focus of=20
this position will be in the semantic aspects of=20
the new proof theory, working mainly with Guy=20
McCusker, Alessio Guglielmi and Paola Bruscoli.

The post will be available for up to 3=20
years, with effect from 1st February 2013.

Web site of the project:   <http://www.cs.bath.ac.uk/ag/ENPS/>

This is our group:

Paola Bruscoli   <http://cs.bath.ac.uk/pb/>
Anupam Das   <http://www.anupamdas.com/>
Alessio Guglielmi   <http://alessio.guglielmi.name/res/index.html>
Willem Heijltjes   <http://www.lix.polytechnique.fr/~willem/>
Jim Laird   <http://www.cs.bath.ac.uk/~jl317/>
Guy McCusker   <http://www.cs.bath.ac.uk/~gam23/>
John Power   <http://www.bath.ac.uk/comp-sci/contacts/academics/john_power/>
Cai Wingfield   <http://cs.bath.ac.uk/~cajw20/>

We are part of the Mathematical Foundations group=20
of the Computer Science Department of the=20
University of Bath. We study the mathematics of=20
logical reasoning, of programs, of processes and=20
of programming languages. In our research we use=20
and develop category theory, game theory, model=20
theory, proof theory, type theory and complexity=20
theory.

Our department has an outstanding research=20
profile: in the most recent national Research=20
Assessment Exercise our research output was=20
ranked fourth out of 81 university submissions in=20
the UK. This year our university has been=20
recognised as third in the country in The Sunday=20
Times University Guide.


